2) Align processor usage with EntityService return types
- The EntityService interface shows these relevant signatures (excerpt):
    CompletableFuture<ObjectNode> getItem(...);
    CompletableFuture<ArrayNode> getItems(...);
    CompletableFuture<UUID> addItem(...);
    CompletableFuture<UUID> updateItem(...);
    CompletableFuture<UUID> deleteItem(...);
  (and others)

- Update processor code so that variables use the return types declared by EntityService:
  - Where code currently does:
      CompletableFuture<ObjectNode> update = entityService.updateItem(...);
    change to:
      CompletableFuture<UUID> update = entityService.updateItem(...);
    and if you previously used update.get() as an ObjectNode, adapt the code. In many places the returned UUID is not used and update.get() was only called to wait for completion — you can still call update.get() (it will return a UUID) but don't assign it to ObjectNode.

- Example edits (illustrative) in CreateOrderProcessor (multiple places):
  - Replace:
      CompletableFuture<ObjectNode> update = entityService.updateItem(...);
    with:
      CompletableFuture<java.util.UUID> update = entityService.updateItem(...);
    and keep update.get(); (but treat its result as UUID if needed).

  - For addItem that returns UUID (when creating an order), ensure you expect UUID (the code already expects UUID when adding orderId; if you used the wrong return type earlier, make sure it's CompletableFuture<UUID>).

- Similar changes in ReleaseReservationProcessor and ReserveInventoryProcessor where updateItem was typed as CompletableFuture<ObjectNode>.

